Uncertainty-based control over the use of one-shot memory for value-based decisions¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Motivation

  • Design

  • Experiment One

  • Experiment Two

  • Experiment Three

Motivation¶

  1. Because decisions are often time sensitive and retrieving a single experience is more computationally expensive than referencing value extracted over many experiences (Lengyel & Dayan, 2008), it is unclear why the brain would develop the ability to resolve decisions using value encoded in one shot.

  2. When prior experience is sparse, such as early in learning or in highly novel environments, artificial agents demonstrate augmented performance when outcomes from individual past choices are considered (Lengyel & Dayan, 2008; Blundell et al., 2016; Santoro et al., 2016)

  3. Biologically inspiried artifical neural networks benefit from shifting decisions based on valued encoded in one-shot to value encoded incrementally ONLY when long-term value is easily estimated (Santoro et al., 2016). This suggests that utilizing incrementally constructed expected value to guide decisions may be a useful strategy only when an agent can be certain that it is possible to estimate such a quantity.

  4. Sampling individual episodes should only be a worthwhile endeavor when it is either difficult to accurately estimate average value (noise) or there is a high amount of uncertainty around an estimate (risk/variance). Thus, we expect there to be greater episodic control over decisions when incrementally constructed estimates are uncertain

Design¶

  • Outcomes for each circle were randomly sampled from normal distributions with equivalent means but differing variances
  • Outcomes for objects were sampled from a uniform distribution. Old objects presented during testing were seen only once during training. New objects were also presented during testing.
  • During training, each participant completed 300 trials in total, where 60% (~180) consisted of choices between objects and 40% (~120) consisted of choices between circles. There was a 30% chance of seeing a previously seen object (~36 trials).
  • During testing, participants completed 150 trials in total, where 50% (~75) of trials featured objects that were previously seen during the training phase.

Experiment One¶

Prediction: Participants should be more likely to avoid objects associated with a value less than the average value ($0.60), and choose objects associated with a value greater than the average value, when the circle’s average value comes from the unreliable compared to the reliable distribution.

Mixed Effects Modeling¶

The following mixed effects logistic regression model was fit using Bayesian inference via MCMC sampling:

OldChosen ~ RiskAversion + EstMeanDiff + ClicksOutOfExperiment + OldValue Reliability + (OldValue Reliability | Subject)

  • RiskAversion was computed as the difference between the proportion each participant chose new objects when the circle is unreliable and when the circle is reliable. Only new objects were included in this measure to separate the influence of risk aversion from memory for objects.
  • EstimatedMeanDiff is the difference between the two circle’s running average value at the end of the training phase. This is to control for the possibility that participants experience the average value of each circle differently, which could underlie choice preferences.
  • ClicksOutOfExperiment is the number of times each participant left the experiment window.

Experiment Two¶

  • In experiment one, many individual objects are associated with values that are beyond the distribution of values that may be experienced when the circle option is reliable, leading to only a subset of cases (between 0.4 and 0.8) with greater competition between object values and the reliable circle.
  • We reasoned that restricting the sampling of object values from this range of greater competition would allow us to measure the PoE with greater sensitivity. Thus, outcomes for each object in experiment two were randomly sampled from a uniform distribution with an average outcome of 0.60 but smaller range: Object ~ Uniform(0.40, 0.80)
  • All other aspects of the experimental design were identical

Experiment Three¶

  • In the previous experiments, participants were explicitly informed before beginning the task that one circle was more reliable than the other. While this instruction helped to aid participants in learning the relative certainties associated with each color of circle, real-world environments typically require such information to be inferred from experience. How might participants’ choice behavior change when they are no longer informed of differences between the circles ahead of time?
  • To investigate this question, we removed all mentions to differences between the circle stimuli from the instructions. Additionally, in order to determine which participants inferred the reliability differences from experience, a post-task questionnaire asked whether participants thought one color of circle was more consistent than the other and, if so, to indicate which one.
  • All other aspects of the experimental design were identical to experiment one.

f, axes = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(18,8))

for rel_id_i, rel_id in enumerate(["Correct","No difference"]):
    
    test_choice_data = ea3.getOverallChoiceProportions(test_data=test_data[test_data.rel_identified == rel_id])

    # Proportion choice for object trials only
    object_choice_data = test_choice_data[test_choice_data.choice_type == "object"]

    p = sns.pointplot(x="choice",y="prop_chosen",data=object_choice_data,scale=0.8,hue="reliability",
                  join=False,dodge=0.4,hue_order=["reliable","unreliable"],order=["new","old"],ax=axes[rel_id_i])
    plt.setp(p.collections, edgecolor=None)
    a = sns.stripplot(x="choice",y="prop_chosen",data=object_choice_data,zorder=0,hue="reliability",
                      dodge=True,jitter=0.35,order=["new","old"],alpha=0.25,ax=axes[rel_id_i])
    sns.despine(trim=False)
    a.plot((-0.5,1.5),(0.5,0.5),'k--')
    a.set_title(rel_id)
    a.set_xticklabels(["New","Old"])
    if rel_id_i == 0:
        a.set_ylabel("Proportion Chosen")
        a.set_xlabel("Object Type")
    else:
        a.set_ylabel("")
        a.set_xlabel("")
    a.set_ylim([0,0.7])
    a.legend_.remove()
    
plt.show()
